Currently, the AutoSave feature is used to protect users against accidental closure of an edit window. One way in which I commonly leave the edit page accidentally is if the cursor focus is moved out of the textarea and I press backspace thinking I will be erasing characters. In situations like this, having an alert that allows me to cancel the page exit would be far more efficient than having to reload the page, then reload the autosave (and hope that the autosave got my most recent changes).

Another more significant hole in the AutoSave is if the editing is on a laptop that has lost internet connectivity -- for instance, the wifi connection got dropped. If anything happens to the page, the autosave will have not happened for some time. Likewise, if the authentication mechanism uses an external authenticator and that authentication times out, autosave will fail.

I would definitely like to see OnBeforeUnload support added to the page editor to add an additional layer of safety.

